ic formation and growth of national identity.These texts best reflect the transformation of Ukraine, and the obstacles to such a transformation, into a modern nation, which in 1991 declared its independence. They serve, therefore, as a guide to a complex period of hundreds of years, which, up to now, was too often considered only as a part of Russian history. In this context, the anthology contributes to an understanding of the past few centuries from a post-colonial perspective.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aNationalismzUkraine. 7aHISTORY / Europe / Eastern.2bisacsh1 aDivovych, Semen, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDontsov, Dmytro, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDrahomanov, Mykhailo, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDziuba, Ivan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFranko, Ivan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGogol, Nikolai, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHrinckenko, Borys, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHrushevsky, Mykhailo, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKacbala, Stefan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKbvylovy, Mykola, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKistiakovsky, Bohdan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKostomarov, Mykola, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKulish, Panteleimon, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLindheim, Ralph, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aLuckyj, George, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/rela